WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
As educators, we want our students to focus on learning, not troubleshooting package installations.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:17.000
RStudio Cloud gives us the ability to install all of the packages we'd like to use for a course or workshop using a base project.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:23.000
This means that all of the packages we need are pre-installed in all of the projects within our shared workspace.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Let me show you how that works.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
From within our workspace, we'll click on New Project.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.000
This will deploy a new RStudio project for us.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Once we have our project, we can install all of the packages we'd like to use for our course.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:44.000
You can either create an R script with all of the package installations, or complete the installations via the console.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:50.000
One benefit to installing packages via the console is that it prevents a bit of confusion for your learners.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:58.000
This is because any R scripts or files that you create in your base project will be available to all of the learners within your workspace.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Therefore, it's possible that learners may run the package installation script, thinking that this is a necessary step in the process.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:14.000
We can name our project anything that we'd like, and for this example, we'll name it Base by clicking on Untitled Project and typing in Base.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Before we can set this as the default for our workspace, we need to make it accessible to all of our learners by clicking on the Settings wheel,

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:28.000
then clicking on the Access tab, and from the Who can view this project drop-down, choosing the Everyone option.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Once our project has been created and made accessible to everyone in the workspace,

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:39.000
we can move out of the project and back to the workspace by clicking on the workspace name in the top menu.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:47.000
From the workspace, we'll click on the Settings wheel in the top right, and from the Base RStudio Project drop-down menu, choosing our base project.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
This now sets up all of our learners with the packages we've installed, but that's not all.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:57.000
We can also create a new base project at any time with additional package installations.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:04.000
Because changes to the base project are not retroactive, any previous installations will be carried forward

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:10.000
along with the updated installations established when we create and assign a new base project.

